social_posts.post_text:
Today is the first Day of Long Covid Advocacy, so I’ve shared 9 black and white photos of things I can’t do anymore because of Long Covid. So many of the things that gave me joy and gave my life purpose have been ripped away from me and my future is extremely uncertain. 💔 I miss traveling, eating in restaurants, being able to eat/digest solid food, I miss attending photography festivals and museums. I miss being able to take long walks and hikes, I miss dancing away my weekends in clubs and being able to attend openings of exhibitions my work is featured in. But most of all, I miss my family so much it makes my chest ache. 3+ years without being able to hug my baby cousins. ❤️‍🩹 Covid has taken away everything from me and you can’t even wear a fucking mask? Now that @joebiden has declared the pandemic over (if it’s over why are 500+ people a day still dying from covid? If it’s over where are my Long Covid treatments?) some states are no longer requiring masks in healthcare and suddenly; it became dangerous for disabled people to even seek medical treatment. Covid has taken all of my dreams and goals and it’s taken away my future. 💔 From bench to bed it takes an average of 17 years to distribute a new medication in the US. Honestly, I’m not sure if I’ll still be alive when they finally approve long covid treatments, so I’m fighting for the next generation of people suffering from post-viral fatigue syndromes. Just like the ME community has fought so hard for DECADES only to be told the illness ruining their life is all in their head. Doctors: believe your patients

3 months after this road trip Covid hit the Northeast US in full force. It took less than a month for the virus to creep it’s way deeper into my lungs until April 20, 2020 when I could feel my lower lungs weren’t ventilating. I couldn’t take a full breath and the lack of oxygen was making me so dizzy and shaky it was hard to sit up. Once the pain became unbearable and I started vomiting and having tachycardia I started to think I wouldn’t live through the night. We discussed going to the hospital but I was convinced if that happened I would just end up dying alone. April 21 I was able to do a telehealth appt with a doctor who prescribed me an “experimental” course of steroids that saved my life. But once the pneumonia started to heal, the rest of my Covid symptoms remained. 3 years later I am still living with these symptoms every day and there are still zero approved treatments for long covid. Millions of Americans are suffering like me and we desperately need support from the medical community and legislators. I am eternally lucky to have my incredibly supportive partner and the worlds best unofficial service dog and cats with nursing degrees. This week lawmakers in Connecticut finally voted to exonerate the 12 people executed for the crime of “witchcraft”, these trials predated the Salem witch hysteria by nearly 3 decades. The innocent were often accused if they farmed land that someone else wanted, the women were often accused if they were widows or midwives or dared to contradict men in public. Women like my ancestor, twice-accused Mary Royce Staples, publicly denounced the existence of witches (holding the still warm corpse of Goody Knapp she said “look what you have done”), she had land that Roger Ludlow (her accuser) wanted and she would speak out in public and contradict men (including her own husband) publicly when they were wrong. The wrongfully executed and their descendants have finally gotten a little bit of long awaited justice

My Great-Uncle Sherwood Olendo “Joe” was born April 18, 1919 and in the brief 25 years that he was alive he was my Grandfather’s favorite brother. He was publicly out as gay in Minnesota in a time when that was very illegal (he died in 1944) and he proudly brought his boyfriends and queer friends home to meet his family. My grandfather was the baby of the family and after losing his father at age 5 he craved the love and attention that Joe and his boyfriends always gave him. Joe died 50 years before I was born but he greatly impacted my family and my own life, it made coming out so much easier knowing that my family would love and accept me regardless. While I’ve researched my family tree I often wondered who my gay and trans ancestors were, was I reading their marriage license without a single guess as to who they really were? Everyone has 2SLGBTIA+ ancestors but their true identities were so often lost to the prejudices of their time. I cherish Uncle Joe for his bravery in living his life authentically and the generational impact that has had on our family 🌈💜
